(a) Plot the sample acf and pacf of 𝑥𝑡 and determine an appropriate ARMA model for the data

library(astsa)
acf(cmort)

acf(cmort, type = 'partial')

Since the ACF tails off and the PACF cuts off after lag 2 we can suggest it is an AR(2) model.

We need to fit X_t - mu = phi1 (X_t-1 - mu) + phi2 (X_t-2 - mu) + W_t. Where phi1 = 0.4301, phi2 = 0.4424 and mu = 88.8538

(c) Use the fitted model to find the 1,…,4 -step-ahead prediction of the series, i.e. 𝑥𝑛𝑛+𝑘,𝑘=1,2,3,4 , and compare your computation with the one obtained by applying the R function “sarima.for()”. Please show the details of your computations.

n = length(cmort)

xn1 = sum(cmort_fit$fit$coef * c(cmort[n] - cmort_fit$fit$coef[3], cmort[n-1] - cmort_fit$fit$coef[3], 1))

xn2 = sum(cmort_fit$fit$coef * c(xn1 - cmort_fit$fit$coef[3], cmort[n] - cmort_fit$fit$coef[3], 1))

xn3 = sum(cmort_fit$fit$coef * c(xn2 - cmort_fit$fit$coef[3], xn1 - cmort_fit$fit$coef[3], 1))

xn4 = sum(cmort_fit$fit$coef * c(xn3 - cmort_fit$fit$coef[3], xn2 - cmort_fit$fit$coef[3], 1))

The 1,2,3,4 step-ahead predictions are as follow:

c(xn1, xn2, xn3, xn4)
## [1] 87.66207 86.85311 87.46615 87.37190

(d) Compute the MSPE (Mean Square Prediction Error) of forecasts you obtained in part (c) (, i.e. 𝑃̃𝑛+1,𝑃̃𝑛+2,𝑃̃𝑛+3, and 𝑃̃𝑛+4) and compare it with the one produced by “sarima.for()”. Please show the details of you computations

coef = ARMAtoMA(ar = c(cmort_fit$fit$coef[1], cmort_fit$fit$coef[2]), ma=0, 50)

pn1 = cmort_fit$fit$sigma2 * (1)

pn2 = cmort_fit$fit$sigma2 * (1 + coef[1]^2)

pn3 = cmort_fit$fit$sigma2 * (1 + sum(coef[1:2]^2))

The manually computed values are:
